    "content": "## Theorem: aime_1983_p1\n\nTheorem: aime_1983_p1\nVariables: x, y, z, w (integer)\nGiven: ht : 1 < x ∧ 1 < y ∧ 1 < z\nGiven: hw : 0 ≤ w\nGiven: h0 : real.log w / real.log x = 24\nGiven: h1 : real.log w / real.log y = 40\nGiven: h2 : real.log w / real.log (x * y * z) = 12\nProve: real.log w / real.log z = 60\n\nGoal: real.log w / real.log z = 60\n\n## English proof (from stage 1)\n{\n  \"key_observation\": \"The three given logarithmic ratios let us express log w as a common multiple of log x, log y, and log(xyz), and comparing these expressions forces a specific value for log w / log z.\",\n  \"plan\": [\n    \"Rewrite each ratio equation as an equality involving log w.\",\n    \"Use the first two equalities to relate log x and log y.\",\n    \"Substitute into the third equality to obtain a linear equation in log z.\",\n    \"Solve that equation to get the desired ratio.\"\n  ],\n  \"steps\": [\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"We have \\\\(\\\\log w = 24\\\\log x\\\\), \\\\(\\\\log w = 40\\\\log y\\\\), and \\\\(\\\\log w = 12\\\\log(xyz)\\\\).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Each given ratio equation can be multiplied by the corresponding denominator, provided the logarithms are defined. Since the ratios are stated as real numbers, the equations are interpreted in the usual way.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of division in equations\",\n        \"h0\",\n        \"h1\",\n        \"h2\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"\\\\(24\\\\log x = 40\\\\log y\\\\).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Both expressions are equal to \\\\(\\\\log w\\\\) by the first two equalities, so they are equal to each other.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 1\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"\\\\(3\\\\log x = 5\\\\log y\\\\).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Dividing the equation \\\\(24\\\\log x = 40\\\\log y\\\\) by 8 gives the simplified relation.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 2\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"\\\\(12\\\\log(xyz) = 12(\\\\log x + \\\\log y + \\\\log z)\\\\).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Using the product rule for logarithms, \\\\(\\\\log(xyz)=\\\\log x+\\\\log y+\\\\log z\\\\), and then multiplying by 12 gives the stated expression.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"logarithm product rule\",\n        \"step 1\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"\\\\(\\\\log w = 12\\\\log x + 12\\\\log y + 12\\\\log z\\\\).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is just the third equality from step 1 combined with the expansion in step 4.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 1\",\n        \"step 4\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"\\\\(12\\\\log x + 12\\\\log y + 12\\\\log z = 24\\\\log x\\\\).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Since \\\\(\\\\log w = 24\\\\log x\\\\) from step 1, the expression for \\\\(\\\\log w\\\\) in step 5 must equal \\\\(24\\\\log x\\\\).\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 1\",\n        \"step 5\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"\\\\(\\\\log y + \\\\log z = \\\\log x\\\\).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Subtracting \\\\(12\\\\log x\\\\) from both sides of the equation in step 6 and dividing by 12 yields \\\\(\\\\log y + \\\\log z = \\\\log x\\\\).\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 6\",\n        \"algebra\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"\\\\(\\\\log z = 60^{-1}\\\\log w\\\\), equivalently \\\\(\\\\log w / \\\\log z = 60\\\\).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"From step 1, \\\\(\\\\log w = 40\\\\log y\\\\) and from step 3, \\\\(\\\\log x = \\\\tfrac{5}{3}\\\\log y\\\\). Substituting into \\\\(\\\\log y + \\\\log z = \\\\log x\\\\) gives \\\\(\\\\log z = \\\\tfrac{2}{3}\\\\log y\\\\). Then \\\\(\\\\log w = 40\\\\log y = 60\\\\log z\\\\), so \\\\(\\\\log w / \\\\log z = 60\\\\).\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 3\",\n        \"step 7\",\n        \"step 1\",\n        \"algebra\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"final_answer\": \"60\"\n}\n\nProduce the JSON formalization.\n\n## Previous attempt (failed)\nYour last formalization:\n{\"theorem\":{\"variables\":[{\"name\":\"x\",\"sort\":\"Int\"},{\"name\":\"y\",\"sort\":\"Int\"},{\"name\":\"z\",\"sort\":\"Int\"},{\"name\":\"w\",\"sort\":\"Int\"}],\"hypotheses\":[\"And(1 < x, 1 < y, 1 < z)\",\"0 <= w\",\"Ln(ToReal(w)) / Ln(ToReal(x)) == 24\",\"Ln(ToReal(w)) / Ln(ToReal(y)) == 40\",\"Ln(ToReal(w)) / Ln(ToReal(x * y * z)) == 12\"],\"goal\":\"Ln(ToReal(w)) / Ln(ToReal(z)) == 60\"},\"functions\":[],\"lemmas\":[{\"name\":\"log_product_rule_3\",\"english\":\"Natural log of a product of three positive reals equals the sum of their logs.\",\"vars\":[{\"name\":\"a\",\"sort\":\"Real\"},{\"name\":\"b\",\"sort\":\"Real\"},{\"name\":\"c\",\"sort\":\"Real\"}],\"body\":\"Implies(And(a > 0, b > 0, c > 0), Ln(a * b * c) == Ln(a) + Ln(b) + Ln(c))\"},{\"name\":\"ratio_to_product\",\"english\":\"If a/b = k and b is nonzero, then a = k*b.\",\"vars\":[{\"name\":\"a\",\"sort\":\"Real\"},{\"name\":\"b\",\"sort\":\"Real\"},{\"name\":\"k\",\"sort\":\"Real\"}],\"body\":\"Implies(b != 0, a / b == k)\"}],\"instantiations\":[{\"lemma\":\"ratio_to_product\",\"terms\":{\"a\":\"Ln(ToReal(w))\",\"b\":\"Ln(ToReal(x))\",\"k\":\"24\"}},{\"lemma\":\"ratio_to_product\",\"terms\":{\"a\":\"Ln(ToReal(w))\",\"b\":\"Ln(ToReal(y))\",\"k\":\"40\"}},{\"lemma\":\"ratio_to_product\",\"terms\":{\"a\":\"Ln(ToReal(w))\",\"b\":\"Ln(ToReal(x * y * z))\",\"k\":\"12\"}},{\"lemma\":\"log_product_rule_3\",\"terms\":{\"a\":\"ToReal(x)\",\"b\":\"ToReal(y)\",\"c\":\"ToReal(z)\"}}]}\n\nErrors:\n- lemma(s) ['ratio_to_product'] are contradictory; refusing to certify\n\nFix these issues and return the corrected JSON object only."
