    "content": "## Theorem: aime_1997_p9\n\nTheorem: aime_1997_p9\nVariables: a (real)\nGiven: h₀ : 0 < a\nGiven: h₁ : 1 / a - int.floor (1 / a) = a^2 - int.floor (a^2)\nGiven: h₂ : 2 < a^2\nGiven: h₃ : a^2 < 3\nProve: a^12 - 144 * (1 / a) = 233\n\nGoal: a^12 - 144 * (1 / a) = 233\n\n## English proof (from stage 1)\n{\n  \"key_observation\": \"Since 2 < a^2 < 3, both a^2 and 1/a lie in intervals where their floors are determined, and the equality of fractional parts forces a specific quadratic relation for a.\",\n  \"plan\": [\n    \"Use 2 < a^2 < 3 to determine floor(a^2).\",\n    \"Rewrite the given equality of fractional parts using the fact that a > 0.\",\n    \"Determine floor(1/a) from the bounds on a and the fractional-part equation.\",\n    \"Derive an equation relating a and 1/a, then convert it into an algebraic equation for a^2.\",\n    \"Use that equation to compute a^12 - 144/a and simplify to the required constant.\"\n  ],\n  \"steps\": [\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"We have floor(a^2) = 2.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"From h₂ and h₃, the real number a^2 satisfies 2 < a^2 < 3, so its integer part is 2.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"h₂\",\n        \"h₃\",\n        \"definition of floor\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The given hypothesis h₁ is equivalent to 1 / a - floor(1 / a) = a^2 - 2.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"By step 1, floor(a^2) = 2, so replacing floor(a^2) in h₁ gives the stated identity.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"h₁\",\n        \"step 1\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"We have 0 < 1/a < 1, and therefore floor(1/a) = 0.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Since h₀ gives a > 0, the reciprocal 1/a is positive. Also, because a^2 > 2, we get a > sqrt(2) > 1, hence 0 < 1/a < 1. Any real number in (0,1) has floor 0.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"h₀\",\n        \"h₂\",\n        \"properties of order under reciprocals\",\n        \"definition of floor\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"1 / a = a^2 - 2.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"By step 2, 1/a - floor(1/a) = a^2 - 2, and by step 3, floor(1/a) = 0. Substituting yields 1/a = a^2 - 2.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 2\",\n        \"step 3\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"a satisfies the cubic equation a^3 - 2a - 1 = 0.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Multiplying the identity 1/a = a^2 - 2 by a gives 1 = a^3 - 2a, which rearranges to a^3 - 2a - 1 = 0.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 4\",\n        \"algebra\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"a^3 = 2a + 1 and a^6 = 5a^2 + 4a + 1.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The first equality is just a rearrangement of the cubic from step 5. Squaring a^3 = 2a + 1 gives a^6 = (2a + 1)^2 = 4a^2 + 4a + 1, and using a^3 = 2a + 1 again to eliminate a^3 is not needed here; instead, substituting a^2 = (1/a)+2 from step 4 is one route, but the key point is that repeated reduction by a^3 = 2a+1 expresses higher powers in lower ones.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 5\",\n        \"algebra\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"a^12 - 144 / a = 233.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Using step 5, every power of a can be reduced modulo the relation a^3 = 2a + 1. A straightforward repeated reduction yields a^12 = 144/a + 233, hence subtracting 144/a from both sides gives the stated result.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 5\",\n        \"polynomial reduction by a cubic relation\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"final_answer\": \"233\"\n}\n\nProduce the JSON formalization."
  }
