    "content": "## Theorem: algebra_apbmpcneq0_aeq0anbeq0anceq0\n\nTheorem: algebra_apbmpcneq0_aeq0anbeq0anceq0\nVariables: m, n (real)\nGiven: a b c : ℚ\nGiven: h₀ : 0 < m ∧ 0 < n\nGiven: h₁ : m^3 = 2\nGiven: h₂ : n^3 = 4\nGiven: h₃ : (a:ℝ) + b * m + c * n = 0\nProve: a = 0 ∧ b = 0 ∧ c = 0\n\nGoal: a = 0 ∧ b = 0 ∧ c = 0\n\n## English proof (from stage 1)\n{\n  \"key_observation\": \"Since m and n are positive roots of distinct cubic equations, the relation a + b m + c n = 0 can be separated by applying algebraic field equations and comparing the resulting linear dependence over ℚ; the only possible coefficients are zero.\",\n  \"plan\": [\n    \"Use the positivity and cubic equations to obtain algebraic identities for m and n.\",\n    \"Show that any nontrivial rational linear relation among 1, m, n would force a contradiction with the distinct minimal algebraic behavior of m and n.\",\n    \"Conclude that the coefficients a, b, and c must each be zero.\"\n  ],\n  \"steps\": [\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"m ≠ 0 and n ≠ 0.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"From h₀ we have 0 < m and 0 < n, so both numbers are strictly positive and therefore nonzero.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"h₀\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"m and n satisfy m = ∛2 and n = ∛4 as positive real numbers.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The equations m^3 = 2 and n^3 = 4, together with positivity from h₀, identify m and n as the unique positive real cube roots of 2 and 4 respectively.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"h₀\",\n        \"h₁\",\n        \"h₂\",\n        \"uniqueness of positive real cube roots\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The numbers 1, m, and n are linearly independent over ℚ.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"If r + s m + t n = 0 for rationals r,s,t, then using the algebraic relations m^3 = 2 and n^3 = 4 one can eliminate higher powers and obtain a rational polynomial relation forcing a contradiction unless s = t = 0, and then r = 0. Since m and n are roots of distinct irreducible cubic equations over ℚ, no nontrivial rational linear relation among 1, m, n can exist.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"h₁\",\n        \"h₂\",\n        \"irreducibility of x^3-2 over ℚ\",\n        \"irreducibility of x^3-4 over ℚ\",\n        \"linear independence from distinct algebraic extensions\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"a = 0, b = 0, and c = 0.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The hypothesis h₃ is exactly a rational linear relation a + b m + c n = 0. By the linear independence established in the previous step, all coefficients must be zero.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"h₃\",\n        \"step 3\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"final_answer\": \"a = 0 ∧ b = 0 ∧ c = 0\"\n}\n\nProduce the JSON formalization."
