 even ones, so the total product factors as the product over odd terms times the product over even terms.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of factorial\",\n        \"partition of a finite product\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"\\\\(\\\\prod_{1\\\\le k\\\\le 9999,\\\\ k\\\\text{ even}} k = 2^{4999}\\\\cdot 4999!\\\\).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Every even integer \\\\(k\\\\le 9999\\\\) can be written uniquely as \\\\(k=2m\\\\) with \\\\(1\\\\le m\\\\le 4999\\\\). Thus the even-factor product is \\\\(\\\\prod_{m=1}^{4999} 2m = 2^{4999}\\\\prod_{m=1}^{4999} m = 2^{4999}\\\\cdot 4999!\\\\).\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"even number characterization\",\n        \"product of a constant over a finite set\",\n        \"definition of factorial\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"\\\\(\\\\prod_{1\\\\le k\\\\le 9999,\\\\ k\\\\text{ odd}} k = \\\\dfrac{9999!}{2^{4999}\\\\cdot 4999!}\\\\).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"From step 2, the full factorial is the product of the odd factors and the even factors. Substituting the expression from step 3 for the even factors and solving for the odd product gives the formula.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 2\",\n        \"step 3\",\n        \"algebraic manipulation\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"\\\\(\\\\prod_{x\\\\in \\\\mathrm{finset.filter}(\\\\lambda x, \\\\lnot even\\\\ x)(\\\\mathrm{finset.range}\\\\ 10000)} x = \\\\dfrac{10000!}{2^{5000}\\\\cdot 5000!}\\\\).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The filtered set includes the odd numbers from 0 to 9999; since 0 is not odd, this is exactly the odd numbers 1 through 9999. The same argument as in steps 2 and 3 applies with the indexing shifted to the range up to 10000, giving the stated closed form.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 1\",\n        \"step 4\",\n        \"relation between 9999! and 10000!\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"\\\\(\\\\mathrm{finset.prod}(\\\\mathrm{finset.filter}(\\\\lambda x, \\\\lnot even\\\\ x)(\\\\mathrm{finset.range}\\\\ 10000))(id) = \\\\dfrac{10000!}{2^{5000}\\\\cdot 5000!}\\\\).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"By step 1 the left-hand side is exactly the product of the odd integers in the range, and by step 5 that product equals the right-hand side. Therefore the identity holds.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 1\",\n        \"step 5\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"final_answer\": \"(10000!) / ((2^5000) * 5000!)\"\n}\n\nProduce the JSON formalization."
