    "content": "## Theorem: amc12a_2020_p10\n\nTheorem: amc12a_2020_p10\nVariables: n (integer)\nGiven: h₀ : 0 < n\nGiven: h₁ : real.logb 2 (real.logb 16 n) = real.logb 4 (real.logb 4 n)\nProve: (nat.digits 10 n).sum = 13\n\nGoal: (nat.digits 10 n).sum = 13\n\n## English proof (from stage 1)\n{\n  \"key_observation\": \"The equation in iterated logarithms forces a simple relation between the two base-4 logarithms of n, and solving that relation gives n = 256, whose decimal digits sum to 13.\",\n  \"plan\": [\n    \"Rewrite all logarithms in terms of base 2 using change-of-base identities.\",\n    \"Let x = log_2(n) and convert the given equation into an algebraic equation in x.\",\n    \"Solve the resulting equation for x and determine n.\",\n    \"Compute the decimal digits of n and their sum.\"\n  ],\n  \"steps\": [\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Since 0 < n and the logarithms in the hypothesis are defined, we have n > 0 and the expressions may be rewritten using base-2 logarithms.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The hypothesis already gives 0 < n, so logarithm identities apply to positive arguments. In particular, log_16(n) and log_4(n) can be converted to base 2 because 16 = 2^4 and 4 = 2^2.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"h₀\",\n        \"change-of-base formula for logarithms\",\n        \"logarithm of powers\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"If x = real.logb 2 n, then real.logb 16 n = x / 4 and real.logb 4 n = x / 2.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Using log_b(a) = log_2(a) / log_2(b), we get log_16(n) = log_2(n) / log_2(16) = x/4 and log_4(n) = log_2(n) / log_2(4) = x/2.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"change-of-base formula for logarithms\",\n        \"log_2(16) = 4\",\n        \"log_2(4) = 2\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The given equation becomes log_2(x/4) = log_4(x/2).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Substituting the expressions from step 2 into h₁ yields log_2(log_16 n) = log_4(log_4 n), which is exactly log_2(x/4) = log_4(x/2).\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"h₁\",\n        \"step 2\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The equation simplifies to log_2(x/4) = (1/2) log_2(x/2).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Because log_4(y) = log_2(y) / log_2(4) = (1/2) log_2(y) for positive y, the right-hand side becomes (1/2) log_2(x/2).\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"change-of-base formula for logarithms\",\n        \"log_2(4) = 2\",\n        \"step 3\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"x = 8.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Let u = log_2(x). Then log_2(x/4) = u - 2 and log_2(x/2) = u - 1, so the equation from step 4 becomes u - 2 = (1/2)(u - 1). Solving gives 2u - 4 = u - 1, hence u = 3, so x = 2^3 = 8.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 4\",\n        \"properties of logarithms\",\n        \"algebra\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"n = 256.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Since x = log_2(n) by definition and x = 8 from step 5, we have n = 2^8 = 256.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of logarithm\",\n        \"step 5\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The sum of the decimal digits of n is 13.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The decimal expansion of 256 has digits 2, 5, and 6, whose sum is 2 + 5 + 6 = 13.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 6\",\n        \"decimal representation\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"final_answer\": \"13\"\n}\n\nProduce the JSON formalization."
  }
