    "content": "## Theorem: imo_1969_p2\n\nTheorem: imo_1969_p2\nVariables: m, n (real), k (integer)\nGiven: a : ℕ → ℝ\nGiven: y : ℝ → ℝ\nGiven: h₀ : 0 < k\nGiven: h₁ : ∀ x, y x = ∑ i in finset.range k, ((real.cos (a i + x)) / (2^i))\nGiven: h₂ : y m = 0\nGiven: h₃ : y n = 0\nProve: ∃ t : ℤ, m - n = t * π\n\nGoal: ∃ t : ℤ, m - n = t * π\n\n## English proof (from stage 1)\n{\n  \"key_observation\": \"The equation y(x)=0 gives a finite trigonometric sum with coefficients 1/2^i; using the standard geometric-series identity for complex exponentials, this sum can be rewritten as the real part of a nonzero multiple of e^{ix}, so its zeros must differ by integer multiples of π.\",\n  \"plan\": [\n    \"Rewrite the cosine sum as the real part of a finite geometric series in e^{ix}.\",\n    \"Use the fact that a nontrivial linear combination of exponentials of this special form has period π up to sign.\",\n    \"Apply the vanishing at m and n to show that the corresponding complex values differ by a factor ±1.\",\n    \"Conclude that m-n is an integer multiple of π.\"\n  ],\n  \"steps\": [\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"For every real x, y x can be written as the real part of a complex number of the form C(x) where C(x) is a nonzero scalar multiple of e^{ix} times a geometric sum in e^{i a i}.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Using cos(θ)=Re(e^{iθ}), each term cos(a i + x)/2^i equals Re(e^{i(a i + x)}/2^i). Summing over i from 0 to k-1 and pulling out the common factor e^{ix} gives a real part of e^{ix} times a finite geometric-type sum.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"Euler's formula\",\n        \"linearity of finite sums\",\n        \"step 0\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The finite complex sum S(x)=∑ i in range k, e^{i a i}/2^i is nonzero as a function of x and can be treated as a fixed complex constant S independent of x.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The coefficients a i are fixed, so the only x-dependence in the complex representation comes from the factor e^{ix}. Thus the sum over i is constant with respect to x.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"definition of finite sum\",\n        \"step 1\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"There exists a complex constant C≠0 such that y x = Re(C·e^{ix}) for all real x.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Combining the previous two steps, we absorb the fixed finite sum into a constant C. Since k>0, at least one term is present, and the resulting trigonometric polynomial is not identically zero, so C is nonzero.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 1\",\n        \"step 2\",\n        \"h₀\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"If y m = 0 and y n = 0, then Re(C e^{im}) = 0 and Re(C e^{in}) = 0 for the same nonzero complex constant C.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is immediate from the hypothesis values h₂ and h₃ together with the representation from the previous step.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"h₂\",\n        \"h₃\",\n        \"step 3\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"For a fixed nonzero complex number C, the set of real x such that Re(C e^{ix})=0 is a union of arithmetic progressions with difference π.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Writing C = r e^{iφ} with r>0, the condition Re(C e^{ix})=0 becomes r cos(x+φ)=0, i.e. cos(x+φ)=0. The zeros of cosine are exactly x+φ = π/2 + tπ for t∈ℤ, so any two such x differ by an integer multiple of π.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"polar form of complex numbers\",\n        \"zeros of cosine\",\n        \"periodicity of cosine\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"m - n = t * π for some integer t.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Since both m and n lie in the zero set described in the previous step, their difference must be an integer multiple of π. Therefore there exists t∈ℤ such that m-n=tπ.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 5\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"final_answer\": \"∃ t : ℤ, m - n = t * π\"\n}\n\nProduce the JSON formalization."
