    "content": "## Theorem: imo_1997_p5\n\nTheorem: imo_1997_p5\nVariables: x, y (integer)\nGiven: h₀ : 0 < x ∧ 0 < y\nGiven: h₁ : x^(y^2) = y^x\nProve: (x, y) = (1, 1) ∨ (x, y) = (16, 2) ∨ (x, y) = (27, 3)\n\nGoal: (x, y) = (1, 1) ∨ (x, y) = (16, 2) ∨ (x, y) = (27, 3)\n\n## English proof (from stage 1)\n{\n  \"key_observation\": \"The equation forces the prime factors of x and y to match in a very rigid way; after comparing exponents via unique factorization and using size constraints, only the pairs (1,1), (16,2), and (27,3) remain.\",\n  \"plan\": [\n    \"First rule out the cases x = 1 or y = 1 directly.\",\n    \"Assume x > 1 and y > 1, and compare prime exponents in x^(y^2) = y^x.\",\n    \"Show that x and y must each be perfect powers of the same integer base.\",\n    \"Reduce the equation to a small Diophantine relation between exponents.\",\n    \"Use divisibility and size arguments to enumerate the remaining possibilities.\"\n  ],\n  \"steps\": [\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Either x = 1 or y = 1, or else x > 1 and y > 1.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This follows immediately from the positivity assumptions 0 < x and 0 < y, since x and y are positive integers.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"h₀\",\n        \"integer trichotomy\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"If x = 1, then y = 1.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"From h₁ we get 1^(y^2) = y^1, so 1 = y. Since y is positive, this gives y = 1.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"h₁\",\n        \"properties of exponentiation\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"If y = 1, then x = 1.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"From h₁ we get x^(1^2) = 1^x, so x = 1. Since x is positive, this gives x = 1.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"h₁\",\n        \"properties of exponentiation\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"Hence, if (x, y) is not (1, 1), then x > 1 and y > 1.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the contrapositive of the previous two steps: any nontrivial solution has both variables strictly larger than 1.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 2\",\n        \"step 3\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"For every prime p, if p^a exactly divides x and p^b exactly divides y, then a y^2 = b x.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Writing valuations of both sides of x^(y^2) = y^x and comparing the p-adic exponent on each side gives v_p(x)·y^2 = v_p(y)·x. This is the standard unique factorization comparison of prime exponents.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"unique factorization\",\n        \"p-adic valuation\",\n        \"h₁\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"There exists a positive integer n and positive integers a, b such that x = n^a and y = n^b, and moreover a y^2 = b x.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Since every prime dividing x also divides y and vice versa, x and y have the same set of prime divisors. Let n be the product of these primes; then x and y are powers of the same integer base n. Comparing exponent vectors yields the relation a y^2 = b x.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 5\",\n        \"unique factorization\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The equation x^(y^2) = y^x implies x ≤ y^2 and y ≤ x.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"If x > y^2 and y > 1, then x^(y^2) would grow faster than y^x in the exponent comparison after taking logarithms; more concretely, the relation between prime exponents from step 5 forces the exponent ratio x / y^2 to equal the ratio of fixed positive integers, so x and y^2 must be comparable. A symmetric argument gives y ≤ x.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 5\",\n        \"basic inequalities for positive exponents\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"In the nontrivial case, y must be 2 or 3.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Using the standard IMOs-style reduction for x^(y^2)=y^x, the bounds from step 7 force y to be very small, because y ≤ x ≤ y^2 and x is also a power determined by y. Checking the resulting divisibility constraints from step 6 leaves only y = 2 or y = 3.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 6\",\n        \"step 7\",\n        \"case analysis\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"If y = 2, then x = 16.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Substituting y = 2 into h₁ gives x^4 = 2^x. The only positive integer solution to this equation is x = 16, since 16^4 = 2^16 and the exponential growth/prime factorization comparison excludes all other x.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"h₁\",\n        \"direct substitution\",\n        \"prime factorization\",\n        \"monotonicity of exponential growth\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"If y = 3, then x = 27.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Substituting y = 3 into h₁ gives x^9 = 3^x. The only positive integer solution to this equation is x = 27, since 27^9 = 3^27 and the same factorization/growth argument excludes all other x.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"h₁\",\n        \"direct substitution\",\n        \"prime factorization\",\n        \"monotonicity of exponential growth\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"The only positive integer solutions of x^(y^2) = y^x are (1,1), (16,2), and (27,3).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Combining steps 2, 3, 8, 9, and 10 yields the full list of solutions: the trivial solution (1,1) and the two nontrivial solutions obtained by substitution.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 2\",\n        \"step 3\",\n        \"step 8\",\n        \"step 9\",\n        \"step 10\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"final_answer\": \"(1, 1) ∨ (16, 2) ∨ (27, 3)\"\n}\n\nProduce the JSON formalization."
