n - 1 < n and n - 2 ≥ 1, raising both sides to the positive exponent n−2 preserves the strict inequality.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"integer inequality\",\n        \"monotonicity of x ↦ x^્ક for positive exponents\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"n · (n - 1)^(n - 2) ≤ n · n^(n - 2) = n^(n - 1).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The first inequality follows from the previous step after multiplying by positive n, and the equality is exponent arithmetic.\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 5\",\n        \"multiplication preserves order\",\n        \"exponent laws\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"claim\": \"n! < n^(n - 1).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Combining n! = n·(n−1)! with the strict inequality from the induction hypothesis and the comparison of powers gives n! < n·(n−1)^(n−2) < n^(n−1).\",\n      \"facts_used\": [\n        \"step 3\",\n        \"step 4\",\n        \"step 6\",\n        \"transitivity of inequality\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"final_answer\": null\n}\n\nProduce the JSON formalization."
